{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585901","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585901"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:21:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:21:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15031"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15031"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.5,0.11,0.14,0.14,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7719"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116263"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7719","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7719"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15031"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98259"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"524"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"},{"type":"tags","id":"8120"},{"type":"tags","id":"10538"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18854"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18860"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116263","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116263"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe alkaline tide is a physiological response that occurs during gastric acid secretion after meals. For each molecule of hydrochloric acid secreted into the stomach, one bicarbonate ion enters the blood.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a consequence of the alkaline tide phenomenon?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased urinary bicarbonate excretion","Decreased blood pH","Increased hydrogen ion secretion","Decreased urine pH","Reduced gastric acid production"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring alkaline tide, gastric parietal cells secrete hydrochloric acid into the stomach lumen while simultaneously releasing bicarbonate ions into the blood. This results in \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased urinary bicarbonate excretion\u003C/strong\u003E as the kidneys compensate for the elevated blood bicarbonate levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased blood pH\u003C/strong\u003E does not occur as blood pH temporarily increases due to the excess bicarbonate. \u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased hydrogen ion secretion\u003C/strong\u003E does not happen as the kidneys actually decrease hydrogen secretion during alkaline conditions. \u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased urine pH\u003C/strong\u003E is not observed as urine becomes more alkaline due to bicarbonate excretion. \u003Cstrong\u003EReduced gastric acid production\u003C/strong\u003E does not occur as increased acid production is what triggers the alkaline tide. The alkaline tide is a normal physiological response that helps maintain acid-base balance during digestion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Alkaline tide occurs when gastric acid secretion leads to simultaneous release of bicarbonate into blood","The kidneys excrete excess bicarbonate in urine to maintain acid-base balance during alkaline tide","This process results in temporarily alkaline urine after meals"],"references":["Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Niv Y, Fraser GM. The alkaline tide phenomenon. J Clin Gastroenterol. 2002 Jul;35(1):5-8. doi: 10.1097/00004836-200207000-00003. PMID: 12080218."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98259"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15031"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98259","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98259"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-28T02:43:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T02:43:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7719"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116263"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"524","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/524"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Gastric acid secretion","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021